# 1️⃣ Doubly Linked List (DLL)

---

# First Understand the Limitation of a Singly Linked List

We learned:

```text
10 → 20 → 30 → NULL
```

Each node knows only:

```text
next node
```

---

## Problem

Suppose you're at:

```text
30
```

and want to go back to:

```text
20
```

Can you?

❌ No

Because 30 doesn't know where 20 is.

---

# Real-World Example

Think of a road:

```text
City A → City B → City C
```

One-way road.

You can move forward only.

---

# Solution → Doubly Linked List

Each node stores:

```text
Previous Address
+
Data
+
Next Address
```

---

# Node Structure

```cpp
class Node
{
public:
    int data;
    Node* prev;
    Node* next;
};
```

---

# Visualization

```text
NULL ← 10 ⇄ 20 ⇄ 30 → NULL
```

Notice:

```text
20 knows:
- previous = 10
- next = 30
```

---

# Mental Model

Think of a train.

Each compartment is connected:

```text
front connection
+
back connection
```

So movement is possible in both directions.

---

# Why DLL Exists

Because some applications need:

✅ Forward traversal

✅ Backward traversal

Examples:

* Browser history
* Music playlist (next/previous)
* Undo/Redo systems

---

# Browser Example

You visit:

```text
Google
↓
YouTube
↓
GitHub
```

Now press:

```text
Back
```

Browser moves using previous links.

Exactly like a doubly linked list.

---

# Traversal

Forward:

```text
10 → 20 → 30
```

Backward:

```text
30 → 20 → 10
```

---

# Advantage

Easy backward movement.

---

# Disadvantage

Needs extra memory.

Because every node stores:

```text
prev + next
```

instead of only:

```text
next
```

---

# Comparison

| Singly LL    | Doubly LL       |
| ------------ | --------------- |
| next only    | prev + next     |
| less memory  | more memory     |
| forward only | both directions |

---

# How to Remember Forever

```text
Singly LL
=
One-way street

Doubly LL
=
Two-way street
```

